k"},"en":{"about 1155–1230":"about 1155–1230","1155–1230":"1155–1230","1165–Female":"1165–Deceased","1179–1243":"1179–1243","1100–1170":"1100–1170","1122–Female":"1122–Deceased","from 1170 to 1230":"from 1170 to 1230","1165":"1165","1230":"1230","1140":"1140","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","1226":"1226","1179":"1179","1122":"1122","1100":"1100","1243":"1243","1155":"1155","about 1155":"about 1155","Rochechouart, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France":"Rochechouart, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France","Rochechouart, Limousin, Kingdom of France":"Rochechouart, Haute-Vienne, Limousin, France","France":"France","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Aimery","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Gloucestershire and Wiltshire, of Norman origin): variant of   Damery  , a habitational name from Daumeray (Maine-et-Loire), France."],"variants":[{"name":"Damery","meanings":["Danish, German: Celebrated soldier."]}]},{"name":"VI","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of   Violet  ,   Vivien  , or   Vivian ."],"variants":[{"name":"Vivien","meanings":["Earlier generally taken as a variant of the boy's name   Vivian  , but now also rarely used for boys. This spelling was quite common in Old French. Its use as a girl's name in the English-speaking world was influenced by  Tennyson's  Merlin and Vivien (  1859 ). This name, from Arthurian legend, may represent an altered form of a Celtic name (perhaps akin to the Irish Gaelic name <i>Béibhinn</i> ‘white lady’, pronounced ‘bee-<b>veen</b>’). The actress  Vivien Leigh  (  1913–67 ) was christened <i>Vivian</i>."]},{"name":"Violet","meanings":["From the name of the flower (Old French <i>violette</i>, Late Latin <i>violetta</i>, a diminutive of <i>viola</i>). This was one of the earliest flower names to become popular in Britain, being used as early as  1700  and becoming well established in the 19th century, although it is now somewhat out of favour."]},{"name":"Vivian","meanings":["Originally a boy's name, from an Old French form of the Latin name <i>Vivianus</i> (probably a derivative of <i>vivus</i> ‘alive’), but now more frequent as a girl's name. The name was borne by a 5th-century bishop of Saintes in western France, remembered for protecting his people during the invasion of the Visigoths."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Aimery VI de Rochechouart Vicomte de Rochechouart was born about 1155, in Rochechouart, Haute-Vienne, Limousin, France, his father, Aimery V de Rochechouart Vicomte de Rochechouart, was 56 and his mother, NN unknown, was 34. He married Lucie de Pérusse des Cars in 1180, in Rochechouart, Haute-Vienne, Nouvelle-Aquitaine, France. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1230, in Rochechouart, Haute-Vienne, Limousin, France, at the age of 76."},"et":{"about 1155–1230":"umbes 1155–1230","1155–1230":"1155–1230","1165–Female":"1165–Surnud","1179–1243":"1179–1243","1100–1170":"1100–1170","1122–Female":"1122–Surnud","from 1170 to 1230":"1170 kuni 1230","1165":"1165","1230":"1230","1140":"1140","1170":"1170","1180":"1180","1226":"1226","1179":"1179","1122":"1122","1100":"1100","1243":"1243","1155":"1155","about 1155":"umbes 1155","Roche